        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1962-01-18T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1962-01-18T00:00:00-05:00" n="273"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d273">
                <head>273. Notes on the Berlin Meeting<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d273fn1"
                        >Source: Kennedy Library, National Security Files, Meetings with the
                        President. Secret. Drafted on January 22.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1962-01-18">January 18, 1962</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="participants">
                    <head>PRESENT</head>
                    <item>President</item>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_RD3">Rusk</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Under Secretary <persName corresp="#p_BGW1">Ball</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_BCE2">Bohlen</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_HMJA1">Hillenbrand</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Secretary McNamara</item>
                    <item>Secretary <persName corresp="#p_DCD1">Dillon</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Attorney General <persName corresp="#p_KJF2">Kennedy</persName>
                    </item>
                    <item>Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KC2">Kaysen</persName>
                    </item>
                </list>
                <p>There was some discussion of pen-pals.<note n="2" xml:id="d273fn2">In particular
                        the latest message, <ref target="#d272">Document 272</ref>.</note> The
                    President indicated to the group that he thought that German self-denial on
                    grounds of visas or the like was not an appropriate basis for the U.S. to take
                    over responsibility for German traffic. Mr. <persName corresp="#p_KFD1"
                        >Kohler</persName> indicated he would convey this point to the Ambassadors
                    in an appropriate way.</p>
                <p>The President asked whether there was any sentiment in Germany supporting more
                    recognition of the <gloss target="#t_DDR1">DDR</gloss>. Mr. <persName
                        corresp="#p_BCE2">Bohlen</persName> indicated that he thought there was. Mr.
                        <persName corresp="#p_KFD1">Kohler</persName> was somewhat more reserved on
                    this.</p>
                <p>Mr. Kohler commented that the British judgment as indicated in the Ambassadorial
                    meeting was the Soviet Union was not in a hurry, and that we ought to pace the
                        <persName corresp="#p_TLET1">Thompson</persName>-<persName corresp="#p_GAA1"
                        >Gromyko</persName> talks accordingly.<note n="3" xml:id="d273fn3">A summary
                        of the Ambassadorial Group meeting on January 18, at which <persName
                            corresp="#p_HLWDOG1">Ormesby Gore</persName> gave this appraisal, was
                        transmitted in telegram 1965 to Bonn, January 18. (Department of State,
                        Central Files, 762.0221/1-1862)</note> The President approved the
                        instructions.<note n="4" xml:id="d273fn4">Reference is to the draft
                        instructions sent to <persName corresp="#p_TLET1">Thompson</persName> in
                        telegram 1681 at 8:06 p.m. on January 18, which stated that the United
                        States was disappointed by the last conversation with <persName
                            corresp="#p_GAA1">Gromyko</persName> and informed <persName
                            corresp="#p_TLET1">Thompson</persName> that it was not interested in
                        accelerating the pace of the talks nor pushing them toward a break. (Ibid.,
                        762.00/1-1862) This draft was subsequently superseded by the text sent in
                        Document 274.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="strong">
                            <persName corresp="#p_KC2">Carl Kaysen</persName>
                        </hi>
                        <note n="5" xml:id="d273fn5">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
